 study investigates how Chaucer's and Gower's texts positioned poetry to become a powerful participant in processes of social control.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aEnglish poetryyMiddle English, 1100-1500xHistory and criticism. 0aLiteracyzEnglandxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aLiterature and societyzEnglandxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aSocial classeszEnglandxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aTyler's Insurrection, 1381. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271062037?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271062037423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271062037/original  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK